Diffusion local times and the time until recombination

Sat Oct 31 12:06:47 2015

\[ \newcommand{\E}{\mathbb{E}} \renewcommand{\P}{\mathbb{P}} \newcommand{\calE}{\mathcal{E}} \DeclareMathOperator{\sgn}{sgn} \newcommand{\grad}{\nabla} \]

Useful functions used below:

source("cline-fns.R")

The goal

The key quantity we compute with diffusion theory is the probability that a lineage, begun at location \(x\) and killed at rate \(k\) when in heterozygotes, is still alive at time \(\tau\). Denote this by \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,k,\tau). \end{aligned} \] Now, let \(q(x,r,\tau,A)\) denote the probability that a lineage begun at \(x<0\) at a location at recombination distance \(r\) from the selected site inherits from the left-hand side of the barrier (i.e., an ancestor on \((-\infty,0)\)) \(\tau\) generations ago. The probability that a recombination occurs between the lineage and the selected locus on either pair of chromatids is \(2r\), and if this happens, the lineage ends up on either background with probability \(1/2\). At this point, its probability of originally coming from one or the other background still depends on its location, but if we assume this is 1/2, for an individual to the left of the barrier (\(x<0\)), the probability of inheriting from the left of the barrier at \(\tau\) is the probability that no recombination at the barrier has occurred, plus one-half the probability that recombination in a heterozygote has occurred, so if \(\zeta = \zeta(x,2r,\tau)\), then \(q=\zeta +(1-\zeta)/2=(1+\zeta)/2\). If \(x>0\) this is the one-half times probability a recombination in a heterozygote has occurred, i.e., \(q=(1-\zeta)/2\). Combining these, the probability of ending up on the left-hand side is approximated as \[ \begin{aligned} q(x,r,\tau,A) = \frac{1}{2} \left\{ 1 - \sgn(x) \zeta(x,2r,\tau) \right\} . \end{aligned} \]

Approximations, generally

We have a function \(p(x)\) (the local proportion of \(A\) alleles), and another function \(f_H(x)\) (the local probability an \(A\) is in a heterozygote), which happens to equal \((1-s)(1-p(x))/(1-s(1-p(x)))\) but we might not want to use that fact; then \(p\) defines a diffusion \(X\) by \(dX_t = \log(p(x))' dt + dB_t\) and then we define \(H_t = \int_0^t f_H(X_s) ds\). We want to know \(\E^x[\exp(-r H_t)]\) as a function of \(x\), \(r\), and \(t\).

More concretely, we want the distribution of the time to first recombination in a heterozygote; denote this by \(T\), so that \[ \begin{aligned} \P\{ T > t \} &= \exp\left\{ - \int_0^t r f_H(X_s) ds \right\} \\ &= \exp\left\{ - \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} r f_H(x) \ell_t(x) dx \right\} , \end{aligned} \] where \(\ell\) is the local time density for \(X\). This is the Laplace transform of the heterozygote-weighted local time, \(H_t = \int f_H(x) \ell_t(x) dx\), so it means that we want to come up with a reasonable approximation to this quantity.

This suggests two possible approximations:

  1. A lineage doesn't go past the hybrid zone, and only recombines when it's in the hybrid zone, which has width something, and where the probability of being in a heterozygote is 1/2.

  2. A lineage spends little time in the hybrid zone, and recombines when it's past the hybrid zone, where it's type is rare, thus replacing both the drift \(\partial_x \log(p(x))\) and the probability of being in a heterozygote \(f_H(x)\) with step functions.

The first one seems more natural, but it requires two parameters: what the width should be and where the barrier should be.

The right model

When the lineage is at \(x\), the lineage recombines to the other background in a given generation with probability equal to the recombination rate multiplied by the probability of being found in a heterozygote. If \(p_{AB}(x)\) is the local fraction of heterozygotes, and heterozygotes have relative fecundity \(1-s\), then the probability of being in a heterozygote is \((1-s)p_{AB}(x)/((1-s)p_{AB}(x)+2p_{AA}(x))\); if diploid genotypes are assorted randomly, then \(p_{AB} = 2p(1-p)\) and \(p_{AA}=p^2\), so the probability that an \(A\) lineage passes through a heterozygote in a given generation is \[ \begin{align*} f_H(x) &= \frac{ (1-s)p(x)(1-p(x)) }{ p(x)^2 + (1-s) p(x) (1-p(x)) } &= \frac{ (1-s)(1-p(x)) }{ p(x) + (1-s) (1-p(x)) } \\ &= \frac{ (1-s)(1-p(x)) }{ 1 - s (1-p(x)) } . \end{align*} \]

Bazykin's approximation to a cline is \[ p(x) = \frac{1}{2} (1+\tanh(-2x\sqrt{s}/\sigma)) \] Here's what that looks like:

tanh_cline
## function (x, s, sigma = 1, log = FALSE, ...) 
## {
##     if (log) {
##         -(4 * x * sqrt(s)/sigma) - log1p(exp(-4 * x * sqrt(s)/sigma))
##     }
##     else {
##         (1/2) * (1 + tanh(-2 * x * sqrt(s)/sigma))
##     }
## }
s <- 0.1
xx <- seq(-15,15,length.out=500)
plot(xx, (-1)*tanh_drift(xx,s=s), type='l', col='red', xlab="space", ylab='proportion or drift')
lines(xx, tanh_cline(xx,s=s), col='black')
lines(xx, 2*tanh_cline(xx,s=s)*(1-tanh_cline(xx,s=s)), col='blue')
lines(xx, tanh_het(xx,s=s), col='green')
legend("topleft",lty=1,col=c("black","red","blue","green"),
        legend=c("p(x)","-log(p(x))'","2p(1-p)","prob of het"))

A lineage does something a bit more complicated, but let's just run a random walk with drift equal to the logarithmic derivative of \(p(x)\), i.e., \[ \begin{align*} \partial_x \log(p(x)) &= -\frac{2\sqrt{s}}{\sigma} \frac{1-\tanh^2(-2x\sqrt{s}/)}{1+\tanh(-2x\sqrt{s}/)} . \end{align*} \] (Really, the drift should be the logarithmic derivative of \(p(x)(1-sf_H(x))\).)

tanh_drift
## function (x, s, sigma = 1) 
## {
##     -(2 * sqrt(s)/sigma) * (1 - tanh(-2 * x * sqrt(s)/sigma)^2)/(1 + 
##         tanh(-2 * x * sqrt(s)/sigma))
## }
nwalks <- 1e4
ntimes <- 4e3
s <- 0.1
tau <- 5
xx <- seq(-15,15,length.out=500)
tt <- seq(0,tau,length.out=ntimes)
rws <- sim_diffusion( tanh_drift, tau, nwalks, ntimes, s=s, xinit=rnorm(nwalks) )
layout( t(1:2), widths=c(3,1) )
matplot(tt, rws[,1:80],type='l', ylab='position', xlab='time', ylim=range(rws) )
legend("topright",lwd=2,legend=c("prob of het","cline","drift"),col=c("black","green","red"))
plot( (-1)*tanh_drift(xx,s=s), xx, col='red', lwd=2, type='l', ylim=range(rws), ylab='', xlab='drift or prob' )
lines( tanh_cline(xx,s=s), xx, col='green', lwd=2 )
lines( (1-s)*(1-tanh_cline(xx,s=s))/(1-s*(1-tanh_cline(xx,s=s))), xx, lwd=2 )

The cline is in green and the local probability of being in a heterozygote is in black; the drift (multiplied by \(-1\)) is in red.

Now let's get local times for those walks.

The exact solution

Let \[ \zeta(x,t,r) = \P\{ T_r > t \} . \] Then the Kolmogorov forward equation tells us that \(\zeta\) solves the following differential equation: \[\begin{aligned} \frac{\partial}{\partial t} \zeta(x,t,r) &= \frac{\sigma^2}{2} \frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2} \zeta(x,t,r) + \frac{\partial }{\partial x} \log(p(x)) \frac{\partial }{\partial x} \zeta(x,t,r) - r f_H(x) \zeta(x,t,r) \\ \zeta(x,0,r) = 1 . \end{aligned}\]

So, let's solve that, numerically. We'll use the ReacTran library, which in 1D solves equations with advection-diffusion parts of the form: \[\begin{aligned} \frac{\partial C}{\partial t} &= \frac{1}{A} \grad \cdot A \left( D \grad C - v C \right) \\ &= \left( \frac{1}{A} \grad AD - v \right) \cdot \grad C - \frac{1}{A} \grad A \cdot v C + D \Delta C \\ \end{aligned}\] which is the same as what we have if we let \(D=\sigma^2/2\) and \(A=p\) and \(v=0\). Here is the setup:

thegrid <- setup.grid.1D(x.up=-15, x.down=15, N = 5000)
clinefn <- setup.prop.1D(grid=thegrid, func=tanh_cline, s=s)
hetfn <- setup.prop.1D(grid=thegrid, func=tanh_het, s=s)
yinit <- rep(1.0,thegrid$N)
tt <- seq(0,tau,length.out=100)
r <- 1

First, two quick checks: First, by setting \(f_H=1\), we should have the solution \(u(x,t,r) = \exp(-tr)\). Then, by setting \(\sigma\) to be very small, the solution at \(x\) should be \(\exp(-trf_H(x))\).

layout(t(1:2))
test.hetfn <- setup.prop.1D(grid=thegrid, func=function(x){rep(1,length(x))})
pde.fn <- function (t,y,parms,...) {
    tran <- tran.1D(C=y, A=clinefn, D=1/2, flux.up=0, flux.down=0, dx=thegrid)$dC
    list( tran - r * test.hetfn$mid * y )
}
pde.soln <- ode.1D( y=yinit, times=tt, func=pde.fn, nspec=1 )
matplot(pde.soln,type='l',ylab="probability of no recomb", col='black',log='y')
lines(tt,exp(-r*tt),lwd=2,lty=2,col='red')
## no diffusion
pde.fn <- function (t,y,parms,...) {
    tran <- tran.1D(C=y, A=clinefn, D=1e-6, flux.up=0, flux.down=0, dx=thegrid)$dC
    list( tran - r * hetfn$mid * y )
}
pde.soln <- ode.1D( y=yinit, times=tt, func=pde.fn, nspec=1 )
plot.x <- sort(match(sample(thegrid$x.mid[thegrid$x.mid>-5 & thegrid$x.mid<5],12),thegrid$x.mid))
matplot(pde.soln[,plot.x],type='l',ylab="probability of no recomb", col=rainbow(length(plot.x)), lty=1 )
matpoints( exp(outer( tt, -r*hetfn$mid[plot.x], "*" )), lty=4, col=rainbow(length(plot.x)), pch=20 )

Looks good.

Now, to solve the real problem:

pde.fn <- function (t,y,parms,...) {
    tran <- tran.1D(C=y, A=clinefn, D=1/2, flux.up=0, flux.down=0, dx=thegrid)$dC
    list( tran - r * hetfn$mid * y )
}
pde.soln <- ode.1D( y=yinit, times=tt, func=pde.fn, nspec=1 ) # note FIRST COLUMN IS TIME
image(pde.soln,legend=TRUE,main="prob of no recomb by t", yaxt='n', ylab='space')
axis(2,at=(pretty(thegrid$x.mid)-min(thegrid$x.mid))/diff(range(thegrid$x.mid)),labels=pretty(thegrid$x.mid))

It's reassuring the solution is between 0 and 1. Let's spot check that with the simulation. Here it is at \(t=5\):

check.t <- function (alpha) {
    t.tau <- which.min(abs(tt-alpha*tau))
    probs <- exp( - weighted_time( rws, tanh_het, s=s, use.t=1:floor(nrow(rws)*alpha) ) )
    plot(rws[1,],probs,xlab='initial location', ylab=paste('probability of no recomb by t=',alpha*tau),ylim=c(0,1))
    lines(lowess(rws[1,],probs,f=0.05),col='red',lwd=2)
    lines(thegrid$x.int,pde.soln[t.tau,],col='green',lwd=2)
    legend("topright",lwd=2,col=c("red","green"),legend=c("mean","numerical solution"))
}

The even more right solution

Actually, the cline gets set up in a time-inhomogeneous way. Let's do that, by numerical solution, then run the lineage back through it. The forwards-time evolution of the cline, with isotropic density and migration, solves the PDE (Barton 1979): \[\begin{aligned} \partial_t p(x,t) = \frac{\sigma^2}{2} \partial_x^2 p(x,t)+ s p(x,t)(1-p(x,t))(2p(x,t)-1) . \end{aligned}\]

thegrid <- setup.grid.1D(x.up=-15, x.down=15, N = 5000)
yinit <- ifelse( thegrid$x.mid>0, 0, 1 )
tt <- seq(0,tau,length.out=100)
fwds.pde <- function (t,y,parms,...) {
    tran <- tran.1D(C=y, D=1/2, dx=thegrid)$dC
    list( tran + s * y * (1-y) * (2*y-1) )
}
fwds.soln <- ode.1D( y=yinit, times=tt, func=fwds.pde, nspec=1 ) # note FIRST COLUMN IS TIME
image(fwds.soln,legend=TRUE,main="mean cline development", yaxt='n', ylab='space')
axis(2,at=(pretty(thegrid$x.mid)-min(thegrid$x.mid))/diff(range(thegrid$x.mid)),labels=pretty(thegrid$x.mid))

Now, let's run the killed lineage backwards in it:

yinit <- rep(1.0,thegrid$N)
rev.pde <- function (t,y,parms,...) {
    p <- cline_interp(tau-t,soln=fwds.soln)
    # p <- setup.prop.1D(grid=thegrid, xy=cbind(thegrid$x.mid,cline_interp(tau-t)), interp="linear")
    tran <- tran.1D(C=y, A=p, D=1/2, flux.up=0, flux.down=0, dx=thegrid)$dC
    list( tran - r * (1-p) * y )
}
rev.soln <- ode.1D( y=yinit, times=tt, func=rev.pde, nspec=1, tcrit=tau ) # note FIRST COLUMN IS TIME
image(rev.soln,legend=TRUE,main="prob of no recomb by t", yaxt='n', ylab='space')
axis(2,at=(pretty(thegrid$x.mid)-min(thegrid$x.mid))/diff(range(thegrid$x.mid)),labels=pretty(thegrid$x.mid))

Let's compare the case where the cline is set up instantly or not:

layout(t(1:2))
fb.p <- clineplot(rev.soln,main="forwards-backwards")
st.p <- clineplot(pde.soln,main="stationary cline")

layout(1)
plot(fb.p,st.p,asp=1,pch=20,cex=0.5,xlab="forwards-backwards",ylab="stationary",col=rainbow(ncol(fb.p))[col(fb.p)])
abline(0,1,lwd=3)

Just forwards

An alternate route to this would have been to solve the coupled PDE for the frequencies of the selected locus and the linked locus.

Comparison, by simulation

Here are distributions of \(T=\int_0^{5} f_H(X_t) dt\) for two different starting points: \(x=0\) and \(x=-3\), and five different models:

  • tanh: the "correct" model;
  • reflected: a Brownian motion reflected at zero and counting one-half time in a neighborhood of size \(\sigma/\sqrt{s}\);
  • reflected tanh: a Brownian motion reflected at zero and counting time weighted by the \(\tanh\) cline;
  • pushed: a Brownian motion pushed back at rate \(4\sigma\sqrt{s}\) above zero and counting time above zero;
  • pushed tanh: a Brownian motion pushed back at rate \(4\sigma\sqrt{s}\) above zero and counting time weighted by the \(\tanh\) cline.
nwalks <- 1e4
ntimes <- 1e3
s <- 0.1
tau <- 10
initvals <- c(0,-3)
lt.comparison <- lapply( initvals, function (xinit) { list(
        tanh=weighted_time( 
               sim_diffusion( tanh_drift,tau,nwalks,ntimes,s=s, xinit=xinit ),
               tanh_het, s=s
           ),
        reflected=weighted_time(
                -abs(sim_diffusion( function(...){0}, tau, nwalks, ntimes, xinit=xinit )),
                function (x,s) { ifelse(abs(x)<1/(2*sqrt(s)), 1/2, 0) }, s=s
            ),
        reflected_tanh=weighted_time(
                -abs(sim_diffusion( function(...){0}, tau, nwalks, ntimes, xinit=xinit )),
                tanh_het, s=s
            ),
        pushed=weighted_time(
                sim_diffusion( function(x,s){ifelse(x>0,-4*sqrt(s),0)}, tau, nwalks, ntimes, s=s, xinit=xinit ),
                function (x) { x>0 }
            ),
        pushed_tanh=weighted_time(
                sim_diffusion( function(x,s){ifelse(x>0,-4*sqrt(s),0)}, tau, nwalks, ntimes, s=s, xinit=xinit ),
                tanh_het, s=s
            )
        ) } )
layout(matrix(1:(length(lt.comparison)*length(lt.comparison[[1]])),ncol=2))
for (k in seq_along(lt.comparison)) {
    for (j in seq_along(lt.comparison[[k]])) {
        hist(lt.comparison[[k]][[j]],xlim=range(lt.comparison),main=names(lt.comparison[[k]])[j],breaks=seq(0,tau,length.out=50),xlab="time in hets")
    }
}

Of course, we aren't actually trying to estimate the distribution of \(T\) itself, but rather the probabilities of recombination (the Laplace transform). Here are these probabilities, as a function of \(r\) (the second plots are on a log-log scale):

rvals <- exp(seq(log(.001),log(0.5),length.out=400))
precombs <- lapply( lt.comparison, function (lts) {
        sapply( lts, function (lt) sapply( rvals, function (r) { mean((-1)*expm1(-r*lt)) } ) )
    } )
layout(t(1:2))
for (k in seq_along(precombs)) {
    matplot( rvals, precombs[[k]], type='l', col=1:ncol(precombs[[k]]), main=paste("x =",initvals[k]), ylim=range(precombs), ylab="prob of recomb", xlab='r', lty=1 )
    legend("topright",lty=1,col=1:ncol(precombs[[k]]),legend=colnames(precombs[[k]]))
}

for (k in seq_along(precombs)) {
    matplot( rvals, precombs[[k]], type='l', col=1:ncol(precombs[[k]]), log='xy', main=paste("x =",initvals[k]), ylim=range(precombs), ylab="prob of recomb", xlab='r', lty=1  )
    legend("bottomright",lty=1,col=1:ncol(precombs[[k]]),legend=colnames(precombs[[k]]))
}

Reflected Brownian motion, killed according to local time at zero

Now, let's look at the analytics for the first approximation.

It states in Takacs that if \(\ell(x)\) is the local time at \(x\) for Brownian motion run for time 1 and begun at 0, i.e., \[ \begin{aligned} \ell(x) = \lim_{\epsilon \to 0} \frac{1}{\epsilon} \text{measure}\{t \,:\, x \le B_t \le x+\epsilon, \, 0 \le t \le 1\} \end{aligned} \] then \[ \begin{aligned} \P\{ \ell(x) \le u \} = 2 \Phi(|x|+u)-1, \end{aligned} \] where \(\Phi(x)=\P\{B_1 \le x\}\) is the Gaussian CDF. Differentiating this, \(\P\{\ell \in du\} = \partial_u \P\{\ell \le u\}\), so \[ \begin{aligned} \P\{ \ell(x) = 0 \} &= 2 \Phi(|x|)-1 \\ \P\{ \ell(x) \in du \} &= 2 \phi(|x|+u) , \end{aligned} \] where \(\phi\) is the Gaussian density.

Let's check this:

nwalks <- 1e4
ntimes <- 1e3
# want total time to be tau, so:
eps <- 1/sqrt(ntimes)
rws <- rbind(rep(0,nwalks), matrix( rnorm(nwalks*(ntimes-1))*eps, nrow=ntimes-1, ncol=nwalks ) )
rws <- apply(rws,2,cumsum)
matplot(seq(0,1,length.out=ntimes),rws[,1:20],type='l', ylab='position')

Here we've simulated 104 random walks for a total of 1000 steps, and scaled steps to have this be a total Brownian time of 1. Let's check; this should just be a standard Gaussian:

xh <- hist(rws[ntimes,],breaks=50,main="final position")
lines( xh$mids, sum(xh$counts)*diff(pnorm(xh$breaks)) )

Now, let's check on the local time formula. The number of steps the random walk spends at position \(k\) on a grid with spacing \(\epsilon\) and a time step of should be \(\epsilon \times \ell(k\epsilon) / \gamma\). First, the local time at 0:

xh <- hist(colSums(abs(rws)<=1.5*eps)/ntimes/(3*eps),main="local time at 0", breaks=30)
lines( xh$mids, sum(xh$counts)*diff( 2*pnorm(xh$breaks)-1 ), col='red' )

What about the local time at other locations? Note there is an atom at 0 now (that is depicted by the dots in the figures below), and that the discretization could trip us up; the colors (red/green/blue) use the (mid/upper/lower) points of the interval that we count in.

layout(matrix(1:4,nrow=2))
for (loc in c(0.1, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6)) {
    lts <- colSums(abs(rws-loc)<=1.5*eps)/ntimes/(3*eps)
    zeros <- (lts==0)
    pred.zero <- 2*pnorm(abs(loc)+c(0,1.5*eps,-1.5*eps))-1
    xh <- hist(lts[!zeros],main=paste("local time at",loc), breaks=30, ylim=range(c(0,pred.zero*nwalks)))
    lines( xh$mids, sum(!zeros)*diff( 2*pnorm(abs(loc)+xh$breaks)-1 ), col='red' )
    points(rep(0,4), c(sum(zeros),pred.zero*nwalks), col=1:4, pch=20, cex=2)
    # lower bound
    lines( xh$mids, sum(!zeros)*diff( 2*pnorm(abs(loc+1.5*eps)+xh$breaks)-1 ), col=3 )
    # upper bound
    lines( xh$mids, sum(!zeros)*diff( 2*pnorm(abs(loc-1.5*eps)+xh$breaks)-1 ), col=4 )
}

Clearly, the discretization is still tripping us up a bit, but it's pretty good.

Its Laplace transform

Now suppose that something happens at rate \(r\) relative to the local time at \(x\) (e.g., recombination to the other background). Then the chance that this has not happened by time 1 is \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,r) &:= \E\left[ e^{-r\ell(x)} \right] \\ &= 2\Phi(|x|)-1 + \int_0^\infty e^{-rt} 2 \phi(|x|+t) dt \\ &= 2\Phi(|x|)-1 + e^{r|x|} \int_{|x|}^\infty e^{-rt} 2 \phi(t) dt \\ &= 2\Phi(|x|)-1 + 2 e^{r|x|} \int_{|x|}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left( - rt - t^2/2 \right) dt \\ &= 2\Phi(|x|)-1 + 2 e^{r|x|+r^2/2} \int_{|x|}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left( - (t+r)^2/2 \right) dt \\ &= 2\Phi(|x|)-1 + 2 e^{r|x|+r^2/2} \left( 1-\Phi(|x|+r) \right) . \end{aligned} \] At \(r=0\) this equals 1, as it should, since it's the chance that nothing happens. For large \(x\), since \(1-\Phi(x) \sim e^{-x^2/2}/\sqrt{2\pi}x\), this is approximately \(1 + 2 \exp( r|x| + r^2/2 - (|x|+r)^2/2 )\), which goes to 1, as it should.

Let's check that, too: why not?

zeta.reflected
## function (x, r) 
## {
##     2 * pnorm(abs(x)) - 1 + 2 * exp(r * abs(x) + r^2/2 + pnorm(abs(x) +

## }

Other values of time

The above restricted to standard Brownian motion on one unit of time. Really, we will want to use this across \(\tau\) generations, modeling a random walk with variance \(\sigma^2\) per generation.

The key quantity we want is the probability that a Brownian motion with variance \(\sigma^2\) killed at rate \(r\) with respect to its local time at \(x\) was still alive at time \(\tau\). Denote this by \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,r,\tau,\sigma). \end{aligned} \] By Brownian scaling, since \(B_{ct}\) has the same distribution as \(\sqrt{c}B_t\), \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,r,\tau,\sigma) &= \zeta(x,r\tau,1,\sqrt{\tau}\sigma) \\ &= \zeta(x/\sqrt{\tau\sigma^2},r\tau) , \end{aligned} \] where \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,r) &= 1 - 2(1-\Phi(|x|)) + 2 e^{r|x|+r^2/2} \left( 1-\Phi(|x|+r) \right) . \end{aligned} \]

Solving the PDE

Let's check this agrees with the solution for the PDE. According to Knight 1981 (Thm 7.4.3), \(\zeta'(0) = - 2 r \zeta(0)\); ReacTran lets you specify the 'flux' at the boundary is proportional to \(\zeta(0)\), where the flux is in our case \(\sigma^2/2 \zeta'\). First note that the solution depends on where we put the boundaries:

# NOTE: must install ReacTran from R-forge, e.g.

The associated cline shape

The Brownian rescaling above tells us how a cline gets wider as time progresses: for a fixed \(r\), the width grows as \(\sqrt{\tau}\). It also tells us that clines with the same \(r\tau\) have the same shape, after rescaling the width by \(\sqrt{\tau}\). Also, this tells us we only have a cline for \(r\) of order at least \(1/\tau\): for smaller \(r\), the locus is still completely linked to the selected locus, and hence a step function.

More generally, here's what \(\zeta\) looks like:

layout(1:2)
xvals <- seq(0,5,length.out=150)

legend("bottomright",lty=1,col=rainbow(length(rvals))[lrvals],legend=paste("r=",round(rvals[lrvals],digits=2)))
matplot(rvals,t(zetavals),type='l',xlab="r",ylab=expression(zeta),col=rainbow(length(xvals)))
lxvals <- seq(1,length(xvals),length.out=6)
legend("bottomright",lty=1,col=rainbow(length(xvals))[lxvals],legend=paste("x=",round(xvals[lxvals],digits=2)),bg='white')

Recall from above that the predicted cline is \[ \begin{aligned} q(x,r,\tau,A) = \frac{1}{2} \left\{ 1 - \sgn(x) \zeta(x,2r,\tau) \right\} . \end{aligned} \]

Here's the cline shape:

Asymptotics

This is very steep at \(x=0\). Notice that as \(x\) goes to 0, \[ \begin{aligned} \lim_{x \to 0} \zeta(x,r) &= 2 e^{r^2/2} (1-\Phi(r)) \\ &= \frac{2}{r\sqrt{2\pi}} + O(r^{-3}) . \end{aligned} \] so that the difference in the left and right limits is \[ \begin{aligned} \lim_{x \to 0-} q(x,r) -\lim_{x \to 0+} q(x,r) &= \frac{1}{2}+\frac{2}{r\sqrt{2\pi}} - \frac{1}{2}-\frac{2}{r\sqrt{2\pi}} +O(r^{-3}) \\ &= \frac{4}{r\sqrt{2\pi}} +O(r^{-3}) \end{aligned} \]

Let's also look at the slope of \(q\) at \(x=0\). Since \(\partial_x |x| = \sgn(x)\), \[ \begin{aligned} \partial_x \zeta(x,r) &= 2 \sgn(x) \left( \phi(|x|) + r e^{r|x|+r^2/2} (1-\Phi(|x|+r)) - e^{r|x|+r^2/2} \phi(|x|+r) \right) \end{aligned} \] and so \[ \begin{aligned} -\partial_x q(x) &= \phi(|x|) + r e^{r|x|+r^2/2} (1-\Phi(|x|+r)) - e^{r|x|+r^2/2} \phi(|x|+r) \\ &\to \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}(1-e^{r^2/2}e^{-r^2/2}) + r e^{r^2/2} (1-\Phi(r)) \qquad \text{as } x \to 0 \\ &= r e^{r^2/2} (1-\Phi(r)) \\ &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} + O(\frac{1}{r}) . \end{aligned} \]

Also note that by the asymptotics for \(1-\Phi(x)\), \[ \begin{aligned} \zeta(x,r) \approx 1 - \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}} e^{-x^2/2} \left( \frac{r}{x+r} \right) \qquad \text{for large }|x| . \end{aligned} \]

Brownian motion with drift above zero

A better model for the process might be Brownian motion that, when above zero, has negative drift, and is killed at some rate. In other words, \[\begin{aligned} dX_t = -\theta(X_t) dt + dB_t, \end{aligned}\] where \(\theta(x)=\theta\) for \(x \ge 0\), and \(\theta(x)=0\) for \(x<0\).

Solving the PDE

Above we simulated the clines deriving from this process.

Analytical form

If we define \[\begin{aligned} \Gamma_t = \text{meas}\{ t : X_t > 0 \} , \end{aligned}\] then we want to know \[\begin{aligned} u(x;\lambda,\theta):=\E^x \left[ \exp\left( - \lambda \Gamma_t \right) \right] . \end{aligned}\] (Small problem: \(X\) isn't guarenteed to be on the correct side of zero when we want it to be.) Well, by Girsanov's theorem, we know that \(\E[f(X_t)] = \E[f(B_t)Z(t)]\) where \[\begin{aligned} Z(t) = \exp\left[ \int_0^t \theta(B_u) dB_t - \frac{1}{2} \int_0^t \theta(B_u)^2 du \right] \end{aligned}\] and since by Tanaka's formula, \[\begin{aligned} \theta \left(\max(0,B_t) - \max(0,B_0)\right) &= \int_0^t \theta(B_u) du + \theta \ell_t(0) \\ &= \theta \Gamma_t + \theta \ell_t(0) , \end{aligned}\] thus \[\begin{aligned} Z(t) = \exp\left[ \theta \max(0,B_t) - \theta \max(0,B_0) - \theta \ell_t(0) - \frac{1}{2} \int_0^t \theta(B_u)^2 du \right] \end{aligned}\] and we want to know \[\begin{aligned} u(x;\lambda,\theta) &= \E^x \left[ \exp\left( - \lambda \Gamma_t \right) \right] \end{aligned}\]

More than we need to know

According to Karatzas & Shreve (1984) (with their \(\delta=\theta_1=0\)), if \(dX_t = -\theta(X_t) dt + dB_t\), where \(\theta(x)=\theta\) for \(x \ge 0\), then if we define \[ \begin{aligned} h(s;x,\mu) = \frac{|x|}{\sqrt{2\pi s^3}} \exp\left[-\frac{(x+\mu s)^2}{2s}\right] \qquad x>0 , \end{aligned} \] (this is the density of the first time a BM with drift \(\mu\) started at \(x\) hits 0), then \[ \begin{aligned} p_t(x,z) &= \P\{ X_t = z \mid X_0 = x \}\\ &= \begin{cases} 2 \int_0^\infty \int_0^t h(t-\tau;b-z,0) h(\tau;x+b,\theta) d\tau db & \qquad x \ge 0, \quad z\le 0 \\ 2 \int_0^\infty \int_0^t e^{2\theta z} h(t-\tau;b,0) h(\tau;x+b,\theta) d\tau db & \\ \qquad {} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}} \left\{ \exp\left[ -\frac{ (x-z+\theta t)^2 }{2t} \right] +\exp\left[ -\frac{ (x+z-\theta t)^2 }{2t} - 2 \theta x \right] \right\} & \qquad x \ge 0, \quad z > 0 . \end{cases} \end{aligned} \] Also, \(p_t(x,z;\theta)=p_t(-x,-z;-\theta)\) gets the same expressions for \(x<0\).

Notes on excursion theory

Let \(n(e)\) denote the excursion measure of Brownian motion, on \(\calE = \{ f : [0,\infty) \to [0,\infty) \, \text{s.t.} f(s)=0, t>s \Rightarrow f(t)=0 \}\). For \(f \in \calE\) denote \(\zeta(f) = \sup\{ t : f(t)>0\}\). Then Rogers 1989 \[\begin{aligned} n(f : \sup_t f(t) > a ) = \frac{1}{2a} . \end{aligned}\] and \[\begin{aligned} n(f : \zeta f > t ) = \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi t}} . \end{aligned}\]
